	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EAC trade integration lags behind schedule </h1>

			
			<h4>
												11 March 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Press analysis in January 2012 maintained that ‘the implementation of the East African Community (EAC) Common Market’ was ‘lagging far behind’ schedule. According to EAC Secretary-General Richard Sezibera, action was required to harmonise national laws to conform to commitments contained in the EAC common market protocol. He observed that trade barriers ‘still exist and continue to undermine the free movement of goods, especially along the Central Corridor (Dar es Salaam–Kigali) route’. At present, ‘Burundi, Rwanda and Uganda incur the greatest cost of non-tariff barriers (NTBs) due to the distance from the main ports of Mombasa and Dar es Salaam.’ However, according to Janet Nkubana, chairperson of the Rwandan Exporters Association, ‘the biggest challenges [regarding NTBs to trade] ‘were encountered in Kenya’.</p><p>It has been reported in the press that ‘Rwanda has begun bilateral negotiations with partner states to eliminate these barriers’. This bilateral initiative with Uganda has been adopted as, according to Rwandan officials, ‘the EAC Secretariat has no enforcement mechanisms to help remove these barriers.’ Although Article 13 of the EAC Protocol ‘requires partner states to eliminate all existing non-tariff barriers to trade and not impose any new ones, little progress has been registered’ to date.</p><p>Press reports in February 2012 however indicated that ‘the East African Community secretariat is working on a legal document to compel member states to eliminate Non Tariff Barriers and speed up common market gains.’ The NTBs to be addressed include:</p>
<ul>

<li>&nbsp;‘infrastructural constraints’, such as bad roads and the excessive use of weighbridges in the absence of common regional road haulage standards; </li>

<li>onerous border formalities; and </li>

<li>congestion and inefficiency at the port of Mombasa, which according to some importer estimates can account for as much as ’40 per cent of the final cost of a commodity’.</li>

</ul>
<p>Despite the problem of NTBs, Kenyan exports to Tanzania are reportedly booming, with the value of exports to the country overtaking exports to the UK. This is attributed in part to the removal of various NTBs to trade, including for example ‘a decision by the Tanzania Food and Drug Authority to ease testing procedures for food exports into the country’. Major food and agricultural items where Kenyan exports are booming include edible oils, maize and wheat flour, sugar and confectionery.</p><p>Beyond the EAC, Ugandan exporters are complaining that the country’s absence from the COMESA trade agreement is undermining their position on the South Sudan market, with companies from Kenya, Rwanda and Burundi, whose governments have signed up to the COMESA agreement, enjoying distinct tariff advantages. This has led exporters to call for Uganda’s early accession to the COMESA FTA. In the interim, a senior government commerce officer reports that ‘there are plans to build the market along the borders’ to supply goods – mainly fresh and processed agricultural products – to both South Sudan and DRC.</p>
		
		
