				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Booming Kenyan exports to Tanzania would appear to highlight the important role that addressing specific NTBs can play in boosting trade. However, the regional export situation also highlights how measures to address NTBs can benefit the members of a customs union unevenly, depending on the ability of their respective companies to take advantage of the new market opportunities.</p><p>It is unclear how this problem of the uneven distribution of benefits from the elimination of non-tariff barriers can be addressed at the regional level. The bilateral process initiated by the Rwandan authorities would appear to offer more opportunities for reciprocal, mutually beneficial action. However such initiatives could serve to fragment the functioning of what is intended to be a common market within a common customs area.</p><p>Looking beyond infrastructural and regulatory NTBs, it is unclear how the EAC programme on the elimination of NTBs will handle the sensitive issue of the use of policy tools such as export bans and other forms of export and import restrictions, in order to bring national practice into line with nominal regional commitments.</p>
		</div>
		
